snippet.textDisplay:
Well, I don't know whether I'm right or wrong, but in my opinion, if you expect someone to treat you as a minor, then you must behave like a minor, both as an idol and as a person. If someone shows some movements or gestures that can induce or seduce people, then you can't blame others for sexualization 'cause all people are not the same. Some people will criticize you and treat you as an object for their satisfaction rather than as an artist, whatever you do. So it's best to be clear from your side.
Nowadays, choreographies contain some movements or dance steps or gesturea that are not supposed to be for a minor, especially in stage performance, yet for publicity and fame; those dance steps are imposed on minor idols. This type of step or gesture can also leave an impact on the minor fan community, which can be dangerous. So I think all idols, whether minor or major, also consider the minor community in case of their behavior both in their personal and professional life as they're the inspiration of many underaged fans.
